Here's a complete example of a C# MCP server that wraps a REST API using stdio transport:

---

## Tool Class (`WeatherTools.cs`)

```csharp
using ModelContextProtocol.Server;
using System.ComponentModel;
using System.Text.Json;

[McpServerToolType]
public class WeatherTools(HttpClient httpClient, ILogger<WeatherTools> logger)
{
    [McpServerTool, Description("Get the current weather forecast for a city.")]
    public async Task<string> GetWeather(
        [Description("City name (e.g., 'Seattle')")] string city,
        [Description("Unit: 'metric' or 'imperial'")] string units = "metric",
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        logger.LogInformation("Fetching weather for {City}", city);
        var response = await httpClient.GetStringAsync(
            $"/data/2.5/weather?q={city}&units={units}", cancellationToken);
        return response;
    }

    [McpServerTool, Description("Get a 5-day weather forecast for a city.")]
    public async Task<string> GetForecast(
        [Description("City name")] string city,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        var response = await httpClient.GetStringAsync(
            $"/data/2.5/forecast?q={city}", cancellationToken);
        return response;
    }
}
```

---

## Program.cs (stdio transport)

```csharp
using Microsoft.Extensions.DependencyInjection;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Hosting;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Logging;

var builder = Host.CreateApplicationBuilder(args);

// CRITICAL: Log to stderr only — stdout is the JSON-RPC protocol channel
builder.Logging.AddConsole(options =>
    options.LogToStandardErrorThreshold = LogLevel.Trace);

// Register HttpClient with a base address for the API
builder.Services.AddHttpClient<WeatherTools>(client =>
{
    client.BaseAddress = new Uri("https://api.openweathermap.org");
    client.DefaultRequestHeaders.Add("Accept", "application/json");
});

builder.Services.AddMcpServer()
    .WithStdioServerTransport()
    .WithToolsFromAssembly();

await builder.Build().RunAsync();
```

---

## How DI Works for MCP Tools

The SDK supports two injection styles:

### 1. Constructor injection (non-static class — recommended for services)

The class is instantiated per-request. DI services go in the **primary constructor**:

```csharp
[McpServerToolType]
public class ApiTools(HttpClient httpClient, ILogger<ApiTools> logger) { ... }
```

Register the service in `Program.cs` (`AddHttpClient<T>`, `AddSingleton<T>`, etc.) and the SDK resolves it automatically.

### 2. Method parameter injection (static class)

DI services appear directly as method parameters:

```csharp
[McpServerToolType]
public static class Tools
{
    [McpServerTool, Description("...")]
    public static async Task<string> Fetch(
        [Description("ID")] string id,
        HttpClient httpClient,            // ← injected, hidden from schema
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default) { ... }
}
```

**Key rule:** Parameters that are DI-registered services, `CancellationToken`, `IMcpServer`, or `IProgress<T>` are **injected automatically** and never appear in the tool's JSON schema exposed to the LLM. Only parameters with `[Description]` are visible to the model.

---

## Scaffold quickly

```bash
dotnet new mcpserver -n WeatherMcpServer
cd WeatherMcpServer
dotnet add package Microsoft.Extensions.Http
dotnet build && dotnet run
```

The server will start and wait for JSON-RPC messages on stdin. Test it with `npx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector dotnet run`.
